 Adoption of soil (protecting something from harm): the case of the Philippine uplands 
 Ma. Lucila A. Lapar, Sushil Pandey* 
 Social Sciences Division, International Rice Research Institute, P.O. Box 933, Manila 1099, Philippines 
 
 Received 11 February 1998; received in changed form 18 June 1999; accepted 6 July 1999 
 
 Abstract 
 Soil worsening in the sloping uplands of Asia is a serious problem that threatens the (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) of farming. Although a few soil (protecting something from harm) technologies have been developed and (helped increase/showed in a good way), their adoption has not been (existing all over a large area). A 
 micro-money-based analysis of adoption of outline hedgerows by upland farmers in the Philippines is conducted to identify the 
 factors that decide/figure out adoption. The scientific results show that adoption depends on a few farm and farmer (features/ qualities/ traits) 
 and the relative importance of these factors differs across places/locations. The high cost of establishment, maintenance and the loss of 
 land to hedgerows are carefully thought about/believed to be the major restrictions to adoption by non-adopters. The money flow/money-based studies of the outline 
 hedgerow system is found to improve (in a big way) if crop (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) or cash cropping is possible. In addition to the need 
 to develop a range of (producing a lot for a given amount of money) technologies, the study points to/shows that in the more not important (surrounding conditions), on-site benefits 
 alone may not be (good) enough to permit investment in soil (protecting something from harm). Â©1999 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 Keywords: Soil (protecting something from harm); Uplands; Outline hedgerow technology 
 
 1. Introduction 
 One of the major factors leading to the unsustainability of farming in the sloping uplands is soil 
 wearing away (Blaikie and Brookfield, 1987). Although the 
 extent of human-like soil wearing away is unknown 
 (Oldeman et al., 1991), activities such as (chopping down trees) 
 and strengthened/got worse land use in the uplands definitely 
 have led to increased soil wearing away. In the humid tropics of Asia, farmers grow a range of survival/income crops 
 in sloping and not important uplands using practices which 
 are often highly erosive (Garrity et al., 1993). In addition to reducing the in-situ working well and (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going), these practices also reduce the (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) 
 of lowland farming through siltation and damage 
 of crop-watering/rinsing with water (set of machines) (Francisco, 1994). 
 * Corresponding author. Tel.: +632-845-0563 
 E-mail address: spandey@irri.cgiar.org (S. Pandey) 
 
 What are the conditions under which farmers will 
 put into use practices which (protect from harm) soil and improve the 
 long-term (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) of farming-based production systems in these sloping uplands? Experiences from a 
 large number of projects put into use in these uplands 
 point to/show that the problem is often not the lack of technology (by itself/in and of itself)  but rather the (can't work together) of the technology (helped increase/showed in a good way) with the (related to how much money and power people have) conditions 
 under which farming is carried out (Fujisaka, 1989; 
 Anderson and Thampapillai, 1990; Baum et al., 1993; 
 Lutz et al., 1994). Engineering solutions such as rock 
 walls, check dams, and terraces have had very little 
 success in creating a wider hit/effect due to their high 
 costs. Other less expensive technologies such as outline 
 hedgerows, outline plowing, and cover management 
 have also been adopted but here and there/rarely. Overall, (related to computers and science) research and (related to telling a lot of people about something) work done so far 
 seem to have had a limited hit/effect in increasing the 
 adoption of (using less of something) technologies. 
 
