 The limited success of these efforts highlights 
 the need to develop a better understanding of conditions which encourage the adoption of (protecting something from harm) practices. Such factors could be farmer-specific, 
 farm-specific, or technology-specific. Farmer-specific 
 factors include the goals of the farmer and the useful thing/valuable supply base. At a wider level, the (related to how much money and power people have) 
 environment under which production happens decides/figures out 
 the useful thing/valuable supply base by allowing useful thing/valuable supply enlargement 
 through market participation. Farm-clearly stated/particular factors 
 are related to the biophysical (features/ qualities/ traits) of the 
 production systems such as soil (features/ qualities/ traits) and 
 climate, as well as the wider (features/ qualities/ traits) of the 
 production system. Technology-clearly stated/particular factors are 
 features of the technology available to the farmers and 
 which are designed to change  the farmers' production 
 systems. This paper focuses on the microeconomic 
 factors conditioning the adoption decision of upland 
 farmers in the Philippines. The paper starts with a 
 discussion of the wider policy and institutional conditions very important for securing/making sure of that soil conservation 
 practices are possibly money-making to farmers. This 
 idea-based discussion is followed by the presentation 
 of results based on an analysis of adoption of outline 
 hedgerows in the Philippine uplands. 
 
 2. The nature of production systems and 
 (rewards or reasons for doing something) for soil conservation 
 As soil (protecting something from harm) is an investment to improve 
 the future productive ability (to hold or do something) of the soil, a microeconomic model of investment analysis can be used 
 to study adoption behavior. A few (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) of 
 such models are available in the books (McConnell, 
 1983; Clarke, 1992; LaFrance, 1992). These models 
 point to/show that the factors deciding/figuring out both the possible benefits and costs of soil (protecting something from harm) depend critically on the nature of the production systems. The 
 (features/ qualities/ traits) of the production system at any point 
 in time is the result of the interaction between the farmers' tries to change it in a particular way to meet 
 their goals and (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al factors which decide/figure out what is (able to be done). The three major (things that decide other things) 
 of the nature of the production system are population 
 density, market access, and the agroclimatic conditions (Boserup, 1965, 1981; Pandey, 1996). A simplified construct based on population density and mar- 
 
 ket access is presented in Fig. 1. When the population 
 density is low and no outside what people want to buy exists, 
 returns to labor are (made as big as possible) by adopting an long/big land use plan, such as shifting (producing crops/helping something grow) 
 based on long unplanted periods (Type I). The farmers' 
 first (or most important) goal in this land extra situation is to 
 set apart work hard to expand the area and not necessarily 
 to improve the produce. As a result of lack of investment, 
 land quality suffers over time until the field is finally 
 rested/fallowed and the farmer moves to a new plot. 
 During the long unplanted period, the natural regeneration may restore soil working well (good or well enough) to allow 
 re-(producing crops/helping something grow) of the field. (rewards or reasons for doing something) to soil (protecting something from harm) under this situation will be (almost nothing/very little). 
 When the land edge of something/unexplored area is closed, further increases 
 in population provide (rewards or reasons for doing something) for (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) 
 of farming-based production so that (sitting a lot) farming systems change (Type II). Farmers attempt to be 
 independent by producing a range of farming-based 
 output under an income mode of production in the 
 (not being there; not being present) of markets. As the scope for increasing the 
 area is limited, the only option available is to improve the yield per unit area by using more labor and 
 other inputs for current production. Labor-intensive 
 methods of soil (protecting something from harm) are likely to be more 
 appropriate to Type II systems. Although investment 
 in soil quality is also a way of improving working well, whether or not farmers will actually do so will 
 depend on a few factors which decide/figure out money-based 
 (rewards or reasons for doing something). Where such (rewards or reasons for doing something) are missing, soil 
 worsening will continue until traveling reduces the 
 population pressure or the area itself is forgotten. 
 When population density is low but market access is 
 well-developed, (large farm with crops)-type made money from production systems are likely to come out (Type III). 
 Once-a-year or repeating food/fiber or industrial crops 
 rule depending on market conditions. On the 
 other hand, made money from production systems are 
 likely to develop when both population density and 
 market access are high (Type IV). Such production 
 systems may be (branched out/done different things) or (made to do one thing very well) depending 
 on a range of conditions. The opportunity to interact 
 with the market in these systems can influence soil 
 conservation decisions in two ways. First, to the extent that cash crops are more money-making per unit area 
 than food crops, an increase in cash crop production 
 would increase the not important value product of soil 
 and encourage the adoption of (protecting something from harm) practices. 
 
