 Income from cash crops will also help relax liquidity 
 restrictions that may restrict such investments. Second, market access will also increase the opportunity cost of labor used for (protecting something from harm) investment. 
 This will make labor-intensive (protecting something from harm) practices 
 more expensive, this way encouraging a preference for 
 labor-saving methods. If such ways of doing things are not available or limited security of (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) restricts the planning 
 (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet), farmers may allow the land to insult/worsen. 
 
 3. (process by which something becomes stronger or worse), property rights, and soil 
 conservation 
 Extensification of land use as a means of improving 
 (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) is not an option in densely-populated areas of Asia. Land use needs to be strengthened/got worse to feed 
 the increasing population. What are the conditions 
 under which land use (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) is compatible 
 with (protecting something from harm)? 
 The effect of (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) on soil conservation 
 depends on the structure of property rights, the level 
 of development of land and capital markets, access to 
 technology and information, and developments in the 
 nonfarm part/area. Security of (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) is a critical (number or thing that changes) deciding/figuring out (rewards or reasons for doing something) to (protect from harm) land quality. 
 
 If property rights to land are (clearly visible/clearly understood) and (able to be backed up with punishment if a rule is broken), farmers will have (rewards or reasons for doing something) to (protect from harm) soil as 
 future benefits from soil (protecting something from harm) will build up to the 
 farmer who makes the investment. Security of (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) 
 will lengthen the planning (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet)  or lower the effective discount rate. On the other hand, if property 
 rights are (not well defined) or are (a law or rule that you can't make anyone obey), a 'mining' 
 plan based on fast (having nothing left/having no strength left) of soil life-creating ability will 
 be adopted. This kind of 'mining' plan can be watched/followed mainly in the forest margins, as well as in 
 quickly making money from areas with (not well defined) property rights (Fujisaka et al., 1986; Cruz and Repetto, 
 1992). For example, farmers who followed loggers 
 in the uplands of the Philippines grew food crops in 
 logged areas for a few years and forgotten the fields 
 later/after that. As these fields did not belong to the farmers, they had no (reward or reason for doing something) to (protect something natural/use less fuel, water, etc.) the productive 
 ability (to hold or do something) of such fields. 
 The possession of a legal title to land is not, however, necessary for securing/making sure of the security of land (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) 
 (Bromley, 1992; Place and Hazell, 1993). Scientific 
 (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) points to/shows that farmers who do not have legal 
 titles have often invested in soil (protecting something from harm) while 
 others with legal titles have not always done so. In 
 many communities, the local land (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) system provides the security of (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) which a legal title does 
 
 244 
 
 M .. A. Lapar, S. Pandey I Farming-based Money flow 21 (1999) 241-256 
 
 not necessarily provide. The local land (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) system 
 can in fact assign rights to own, use, and move (from one place to another) land 
 in the same way that a legal title does, but often at a 
 much lower cost due to community enforcement. In 
 fact, attempts by governments to replace the community land (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) system by legal titles that are expensive 
 to enforce have often increased the (state of not being safe/source of mental worry) of land 
 (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) in many (communities of people) (Bromley, 1992). 
 How do the property rights to land change as land 
 use is stronger? The explanation of caused invention of new things 
 points to/shows that when the land use strength is low, the 
 property rights to land tend to be non-specific and 
 usufruct (Hayarni and Ruttan, 1985; Binswanger and 
 Pingali, 1987). As the land use strength increases due 
 to population pressure and/or expanded export opportunities, property rights become more specific with 
 rights to own, use, and move (from one place to another). The natural (change over time) 
 of property rights to land from general to specific 
 rights breaks down if (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) happens at a pace 
 faster than the ability (to hold or do something) of local institutions to change to fit 
 the changes in property rights or if government policies interfere with such a natural (change over time). When (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) happens in response to fast traveling to a newly 
 opened area, the natural process of (change over time) of property rights tends to break down leading to adoption 
 of farming-based practices that are not (able to last/helping the planet) 
 (Fujisaka et al., 1986). If such areas happen to be 
 sloping uplands with highly (able to be easily worn away by rain, wind, etc.) soils, land worsening in such (communities of people) can be a extreme problem. 
 The existence of (clearly visible/clearly understood) and (able to be backed up with punishment if a rule is broken) property rights to land is a necessary but not a (good) enough 
 condition to adoption. The adoption of soil (protecting something from harm) practices is dependent on the existence of a few 
 added/more conditions. A poorly-developed land market may not (make a part of you) land quality improvements 
 in land values, this way discouraging the adoption of (protecting something from harm) practices. (in almost the same way), a poorly-developed capital market may hold back adoption by limiting money 
 available for such investments. Soil (protecting something from harm) in 
 the sloping uplands may be more effective if put into use at the (related to an area of land that drains into a river) level. Without strong community level enforcement, such efforts could be frustrated/blocked 
 by the free-rider problem. The adoption of (protecting something from harm) practices in the uplands is also tied up with 
 the macro and part/areaal policies that decide/figure out (rewards or reasons for doing something) for different land use patterns (Cruz and Repetto, 
 1992; Coxhead and Jayasuriya, 1994). Some types of 
 land use are soil eroding while others are soil conserv- 
 
 ing. For example, soil wearing away under most repeating 
 crops is (almost nothing/very little) as such crops provide a continuous 
 year-round ground cover. On the other hand, the production of once-a-year food crops tends to cause more wearing away unless healing measures are begun/tried. When 
 faced with rising population, limited off-farm employment opportunities, and limited access to markets, upland farmers may have no other choice but to strengthen 
 the production of staple food using an income mode 
 of production even though the long-run (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) 
 is threatened. The history of upland development in 
 the Philippines, Vietnam, and Thailand highlights the 
 effect of macro and part/areaal policies on the adoption 
 of (protection of natural things/using less energy, water, etc.) practices very well. The traveling of 
 lowland population to the uplands in the Philippines 
 in the 70s and 80s has been attributed mainly to the 
 spoiled working well of rice in the lowlands, a high 
 rate of population growth and low (able to/ability to hold or take in something else) ability (to hold or do something) of the nonfarm part/area. The traveling, joined with 
 poorly defined property rights in the uplands, is carefully thought about/believed to be a major factor causing soil wearing away in 
 the uplands. Also, the (with a too-high value assigned) exchange rate 
 encouraged the production of food crops at the cost 
 of repeating export crops. (in almost the same way) in Vietnam, the 
 government policy of (related to a large area) food independence 
 until the late 80s was a major factor for the (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of area under shifting (producing crops/helping something grow) and the resulting soil wearing away. On the other hand, improved market 
 access through increased investment in (set of machines) 
 in the uplands helped (branch out into different things) the upland production systems in Thailand (Shinawatra, 1985). The (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) and market (combination of different things together that work as one unit) not only relaxed 
 the liquidity restrictions to investment in conservation 
 practices faced by upland farmers, but also improved 
 their food security with the coming into view of land use 
 patterns based on (serving to compare two or more things) advantage. Also, the fast growth in the nonfarm part/area helped 
 to take-off the excess population from these delicate 
 upland areas and (after that) reduced the pressure 
 for (process by which something becomes stronger or worse). 
 With the right mix of policy and institutional helping actions, there is no reason why (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) cannot 
 be (accomplished or gained) sustainably. The Machakos experience in 
 Kenya is a case in point. (even though there is the existence of) a five-fold increase 
 in population, Machakos residents were able to increase per person farming-based output through a correct 
 mix of institutional and inventionss 
 and improved linkage with the nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 
 M .. A. Lapar, S. Pandey/ Farming-based Money flow 21 (1999) 241-256 
 
 (English et al., 1994). Although the Machakos experience may not be repeatable in many of the Asian 
 uplands, it highlights the importance of different policy 
 and institutional options in encouraging the adoption 
 of (able to last/helping the planet) practices. 
 
 4. Some microeconomic (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) from the 
 Philippines 
 4.1. Study area and sampling design 
 Claveria and Cebu are the two major places/locations in the 
 Philippines where the outline hedgerow technology 
 was actively (helped increase/showed in a good way) in the early 80s. The World 
 Neighbors, in cooperation with the Department of 
 (surrounding conditions) and Natural Useful things/valuable supplies, (helped increase/showed in a good way) a 
 range of soil (protecting something from harm) practices including outline hedgerows in Cebu in the early 80s. The soil 
 conservation technology was a part of the 
 overall technology to encourage a move/change in production 
 systems from survival/income to cash crops. Overall, the 
 outline hedgerow technology has spread around the 
 initial target area and the Cebu case is often referred to as 
 a successful example of adoption of soil conservation 
 technology (Garcia and Gerrits, 1995). 
 In 1985, the International Rice Research Institute 
 started a farming systems research program in the 
 acid uplands of Claveria, Misamis Oriental in cooperation with the Department of Farming. A outline hedgerow-based farming system was (helped increase/showed in a good way) 
 using the farmer-to-farmer extension approach based 
 on the plan of the World Neighbors in Cebu 
 (Fujisaka and Garrity, 1988). Sixty-four out of 182 
 farmers trained had established outline hedgerows by 
 the end of 1990 (Fujisaka, 1993). A later study 
 by Cenas and Pandey (1996) recorded/supported the status 
 of the outline hedgerow systems of these farmers 
 in 1995. While outline hedgerows were thought about/believed 
 ineffective and (after that) forgotten by about 
 25% of the first adopters, others changed and/or 
 maintained their hedgerow structures. 
 This study focuses on the outline hedgerow technology as a soil (protecting something from harm) practice. A sample of 130 
 farmers consisting of74 adopters and 56 non-adopters 
 was selected from Cebu and Claveria. The city of 
 Cebu provides a good market outlet for commercial 
 
 245 
 
 production from the peri-city-based  sloping areas. On the 
 other hand, the market for the products from Claveria 
 which is located in the area of control/area of land of Misamis Oriental 
 is somewhat limited to the smaller city of Cagayan de 
 Oro. The population densities in the areas of Cebu 
 and Misarnis Oriental are 574 people per km2 and 
 285 people per km2 , (match up each pair of items in order) (NCSO, 1997). The 
 study area in Cebu comes under Cebu City which has 
 a population density of 2358 people per km2 . So, 
 in terms of Fig. 1, Cebu represents an area with good 
 market access and high population density, whereas 
 Claveria represents an area with a lower population 
 density and somewhat limited market access. 
 The sampling design used to select farmers was 
 layered purposive. As the goal of the study is to 
 carry out an in-depth analysis of adoption behavior, 
 farmers were divided into two layers, namely adopters 
 and non-adopters. Adopters were defined as farmers 
 who have established outline hedgerows in at least 
 one parcel of their farms, were helping grow and maintaining their smoothly shaped parcels, and had crop production during the year before the survey year. The 
 sample consisted of 39 adopters and 21 non-adopters 
 from nine villages in Claveria and 35 adopters and 
 35 non-adopters from six villages in Cebu. In order to reduce the effect of (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) differences/different versions, 
 non-adopters were selected from the same villages 
 and, where possible, were farmers with fields next to the outline hedgerow fields of the adopters. 
 Given the purposive nature of the sampling design, 
 caution should be exercised in predicting the farm 
 and farmer (features/ qualities/ traits) of the sample farmers to the 
 overall population. 
 A structured list of questions was used for the field 
 interviews. Described/explained information on production systems, input use, costs and returns, nature and extent of adoption of outline hedgerows, adoption 
 of soil (protecting something from harm) practices other than outline 
 hedgerows, and farmers' perceptions (related to/looking at/thinking about) advantages/disadvantages of outline hedgerows were 
 collected. Interviews with key informants including 
 government (people in charge), non-government organizations, 
 and other government (services businesses/government units) working at soil (protecting something from harm) were also managed and did/done. 
 The farm level data on production systems collected 
 during the survey has to do with the 1995 cropping season. 
 The basic (features/ qualities/ traits) of the production systems in 
 these two locations are summarized in Table 1. While 
 
