 4.2. (features/ qualities/ traits) of adoption and adopters 
 The extent of adoption, as measured by the proportion of farm area with outline hedgerows of 
 families who have adopted the technology and the 
 proportion of farmers who have established outline 
 hedgerows in the whole farm, is higher in Cebu than 
 in Claveria (Table 2). Adoption started earlier in Cebu 
 where almost a quarter of the sample farmers have 
 adopted outline hedgerows for more than 10 years. 
 Adopters of outline hedgerows in both Cebu and 
 Claveria have a larger proportion of farm area under 
 cash crops than under survival/income crops (Table 3). 
 The adoption of outline hedgerows may have encouraged a move/change towards cash cropping 1 . The heads 
 of families that have adopted outline hedgerows 
 are younger and have more years of education. A 
 larger proportion of families that have adopted 
 outline hedgerows are members of alayon, a local 
 labor-sharing group, and have received training in soil 
 conservation for a (a) little longer period compared to 
 those of non-adopters. Also, a larger proportion 
 of adopters own at least a parcel of the land they are 
 1 If the (things causing other things to happen) runs in this direction, the opportunity cost of 
 not adopting outline hedgerows is the income from cash cropping 
 forgone. Benefit-cost analysis of (protection of natural things/using less energy, water, etc.) practice based only 
 on the difference in yield of food crops with and without outline 
 hedgerow will underestimate the money-based value. 
 
 4.3. (features/ qualities/ traits) of outline hedgerows 
 Based on the combined data for Cebu and Claveria, 
 the average height of the riser 2 is guessed to be 
 0.8 m.lt is found to be positively related to the number 
 of years of adoption. The average once-a-year increase in 
 the height of the riser is guessed at 5 em per year. 
 The average width of the hedgerows is 1.3 m and the 
 average length of hedgerows per hectare smoothly shaped is 
 1300m. 
 Natural grasses are the most important hedgerow 
 species (Table 4). Napier grass is the second most 
 commonly used species. A larger proportion of smoothly shaped parcels in Cebu are planted with Napier grass 
 compared to those in Claveria. Due to the limited 
 grazing area in Cebu, farmers think about/believe Napier grass 
 hedgerows to be valuable as food. Other hedgerow 
 species used are gliricidia (Gliricidia sepium), setaria 
 (Setaria sp.), and leucaena (Leucaena leucocephala). 
 There appears to be a movement towards natural 
 grass-based hedgerows which is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the 
 results of a previous study done in Claveria by Cenas 
 and Pandey (1996). While only about 8% ofthe fields 
 started out with natural grass as hedgerow species and 
 have remained that way, 35% of the fields have shifted 
 from planted species to natural grasses as hedgerow 
 species. Natural rule of grasses and high death of the planted species are the major reasons referred to 
 for a move/change towards a natural grass-based system. 
