 to begin/try than outline hedgerows. The hint/result/effect 
 
 is that (help increase/show in a good way)rs of soil (protecting something from harm) in the uplands 
 must not view outline hedgerows as the universal solution for all farmers but only as one of the options. 
 If a wider range of methods is (helped increase/showed in a good way), farmers will 
 have the flexibility to choose practices that they think about/believe to be the most appropriate to their fields. 
 
 4.5. Factors deciding/figuring out adoption 
 
 The adoption data were carefully studied using a probit 
 model (Maddala, 1983; Greene, 1997) to identify the 
 factors deciding/figuring out the adoption of outline hedgerows 
 for soil (protecting something from harm). Some (numbers that change/things that change) are guessed to decide/figure out the farmer's decision to adopt 
 a soil (protecting something from harm) technology. These (numbers that change/things that change) are 
 classified into four categories, namely, personal factors, money-based (numbers that change/things that change), institutional factors and the 
 soil wearing away (possible power or ability within/possibility of)  the field. Descriptive statistics of these (numbers that change/things that change) and their expected effects are 
 summarized in Table 5. 
 The effect of age of the farmer on adoption decision 
 can be taken as a (thing made up of different things) of the effects of farming 
 experience and planning (line in the distance where the Earth and sky meet). While longer farming experience as equated with older farmers is expected to have a positive effect on adoption, younger 
 farmers, on the other hand, may have longer planning 
 horizons and, because of this, may be more likely to invest in 
 conservation. The net effect on adoption, therefore, 
 could not be serious and stubborn good. Hoover and Wiitala 
 (1980) found in their study of Nebraska farmers that 
 age has a significant negative influence on adoption. 
 College levels may be connected with 
 greater information on (protecting something from harm) measures and 
 the working well results of wearing away, and higher 
 management intelligence (Ervin and Ervin, 1982; Hoover 
 and Wiitala, 1980; Feder et al., 1985). As a human 
 capital (number or thing that changes), education is also found to positively 
 affect the (wasting very little while working or producing something) of adoption of (using less of something) practices (Rahm and Huffman, 1984). Because of this adoption 
 is guessed to be positively related to the 
 farmer's education level. 
 Membership in local labor exchange groups, called 
 alayon, is suggested/said to have a positive effect on adoption. 
